<TEXT>
radio talk show hosts proved theyre a force to be 
reckoned with during the congressional payraise brouhaha deluging 
capitol hill with millions of tea bags from angry listeners but 
they still feel ignored 
so theyre meeting in boston this weekend to do what other 
aggrieved minorities do unite to demand more power 
in the words of rodney dangerfield we dont get no 
respect said organizer jerry williams of boston radio station 
wrko the national media never took us very seriously they 
think theres some conspiracy here 
about 50 of the countrys 225 radio talk show hosts began 
arriving friday for the inaugural talkradio conference a twoday 
gab confab expected to include consumer activist ralph nader tv 
talk show host morton downey jr and political columnist jack 
anderson 
williams a 65yearold talk jockey whos been in the business 
since 1950 said he hoped the gathering would give visibility to a 
national movement that has given ordinary people a chance to be 
heard 
theres a huge void where people feel they dont have a voice 
anymore he said 
the voices at the conference are deep and smooth the smiles are 
big the words are vehement and wellrehearsed 
there is no more representative government in this country 
anymore its all special interests said mills crenshaw of 
wtkkam in salt lake city the reason politicians are afraid of 
talk radio is we have the ability to allow private citizens to talk 
to their government 
williams took the first step toward unifying the talk show hosts 
in february when he was able to persuade his colleagues to lead a 
national protest against proposed federal pay increases 
coaxed by their local hosts listeners sent their congressmen a 
ton of tea bags bearing the message read my tea bag no 50 
percent raise 
the public pressure helped halt a raise for lawmakers judges and 
other people on the federal payroll 
williams said he was encouraged by the cooperation of his onair 
brethren to try to formalize their connections through a conference 
the session got going friday with an open mike to boston area 
listeners today the talk show hosts planned to talk to each other 
exchanging ideas and formally organizing williams said 
faneuil hall the venerable brick building where revolutionaries 
fomented independence from britain and abolitionists railed against 
slavery served as the stage for fridays events 
in the morning wrko host gene burns leaned into one of the 
microphones and said the people are sovereign not the 
government adding 
our elected representatives try to give americans enough 
fat from the hog to keep people from rising up 
his peers from across the country and about 125 listeners from 
around new england took their seats and in person the talk show 
fans were as vociferous as their radio friends 
i like to hear what the people say and not the politicians we 
have a governor here whos a dictator said z peter czapski 67 
of north andover his face turning red 
youve got me going the retired tool and die plant manager 
said happily 
janet wofsey 36 of quincy who works for a department store 
said shes a frequent listener and talker 
its the satisfaction of voicing my opinion to express it over 
the airwaves with letter writing theres no response she said 
you can get a response from the talk show 
