some of the most promising research dealt with the development of 
new drugs for aids 
azt is extending the life span of aids patients but it has toxic 
side effects and in a disturbing development studies have shown 
that the aids virus can develop a resistance to azt making the drug 
no longer effective 
the surprise is it took this long to discover it said dr 
robert yarchoan of the us national cancer institute 
on the other hand the virus strains resistant to azt do not seem 
to be resistant to other aztlike drugs now under study thats 
been a surprise on the good side yarchoan said 
azt is one of a class of drugs called reverse transcriptase 
inhibitors it mimics genetic building blocks needed by the aids 
virus to link with genes inside cells to make more virus 
two newer drugs under study ddc and ddi work the same way and 
are among the most promising new agents said dr thomas merigan of 
stanford university a member of the committee overseeing federal 
drug trials in the united states 
as with cancer treatment the use of a combination of drugs might 
maximize their beneficial effects while minimizing their side 
effects he said 
perhaps the most exciting new drugs are socalled soluble cd4 and 
its relatives these drugs interfere with the process by which the 
aids virus invades cells 
they have to add up to one of our best prospects merigan 
said 
studies are just starting to show that cd4 can reduce levels of 
virus in the body he said whether that will improve the health of 
infected people is not yet known 
some drugs that have been tested have flopped they include 
dextran sulfate which looked promising a year or two ago and 
al721 a drug that many aids patients had pushed for 
merigan said he doubted the usefulness of dextran sulfate from 
the start but that 50 patients were used to study the drug in 
response to pressure and criticism from congress 
it means that our ddc study would have been 50 patients ahead 
if we didnt have this pressure he said 
but merigan said researchers are working as quickly as possible 
to evaluate new drugs 
broder predicted that the experimental results and the aids 
patients survival curves would be even better next year and the 
year after that 
