<TEXT>
george w beadle a nobel prizewinning 
biologist and former president of the university of chicago died 
after a long illness he was 85 
beadle died friday at a nursing home in this southern california 
town relatives didnt supply the cause of death but said he had 
been suffering from alzheimers disease said university spokesman 
jonathan kleinbard 
george beadle was an enormously distinguished scientist of 
great personal qualities and quiet personal force he presided over 
a very important period of significant growth and enduring renewal 
for the university of chicago said school president hanna gray 
beadle shared the nobel prize in physiology and medicine in 1948 
with edward tatum and joshua lederberg for their discovery that 
genes act by controlling enzymes that direct chemical reactions 
his later studies clarified the origins of domestic corn and he 
was the author of a number of books on genetics 
he was named president of the university of chicago in 1961 and 
retired in 1968 
beadle was born oct 22 1903 on a farm near wahoo neb he 
received his doctorate degree from cornell university in 1931 
he taught at harvard and stanford universtities and the 
california institute of technology before coming to chicago 
beadle is survived by his wife muriel barnett beadle of pomona 
his sister ruth his sons redmond barnett and david beadle and 
five grandchildren 
